    },
    {
      "turn_number": 20,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I honestly expected one steady person — a midwife or provider who’d learn the shape of my story: 41, a previous loss, juggling a job, and all the small anxieties that come with that. I wanted someone who’d notice when I was quieter, who would remember the details without me repeating them, who could say, “I know you — we’ll watch this together.”\n\nInstead, care has felt patchwork. Sometimes I see my obstetrician and feel heard; other visits are with strangers — a different nurse, a lab tech, a rotating resident. The clinical competence is there, mostly, but the emotional continuity isn’t. That matters to me more than I expected: after a loss, every visit felt like starting over. It’s exhausting to re-tell the same fears each time, to explain why a simple NIPT blood draw sends my heart racing. I’m grateful for the professionalism, but I miss having a single trusted person to hold the thread of this pregnancy with me.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "V4_PREG_Q03",
      "input_tokens": 1177,
      "output_tokens": 469
    },
    {
      "turn_number": 21,
      "role": "interviewer",
      "type": "question",
      "text": "During pregnancy, what did you expect in terms of how your changing body would be discussed and examined by healthcare providers? And how did those interactions actually feel?",
