    },
    {
      "turn_number": 28,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I imagined people would rally around me — my mom bringing soup, a friend texting throughout the first ultrasound, my husband taking time off work for appointments, colleagues being understanding about the morning sickness and the doctor visits. I wanted small practical things as much as big gestures: someone to sit with me after a scary result, someone to say it’s okay to be terrified.\n\nThe reality has been mixed. My husband has been steady and kind, but he’s also juggling his job so he can’t always be there. My mother is cautiously optimistic; she’s helpful but quiet, like she’s scared to jinx things after our loss. Some friends have been wonderfully present; others have pulled back, maybe unsure how to support without saying the wrong thing. At work I’ve mostly kept the news close — people are polite but I don’t feel sheltered. That patchwork of support leaves me grateful for the kindness I do get, and lonely for the deeper, consistent care I hoped for.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "V4_PREG_Q07",
      "input_tokens": 1570,
      "output_tokens": 461
    },
